11. setup instructions
Use Supabase’s SSR package pattern for Next.js App Router, with cookie-based server/browser clients and middleware-based session refresh. Supabase’s current SSR docs recommend @supabase/ssr for this flow. Gemini’s structured output docs support JSON Schema-constrained responses, which is what the prompt layer here uses for reliable parsing. �
Supabase +1
Fill these env variables
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY
GEMINI_API_KEY
GEMINI_MODEL
NEXT_PUBLIC_PRO_UPGRADE_URL
What NEXT_PUBLIC_PRO_UPGRADE_URL does
All upgrade CTAs in the UI point to this URL.
Examples:
Stripe checkout link
Lemon Squeezy checkout link
billing portal link
sales/contact page
If you do not set it, the app still works, but upgrade buttons will fall back to the pricing page.
Supabase setup
Create a Supabase project.
Open SQL Editor.
Paste the full contents of supabase/schema.sql.
Run it.
In Project Settings → API, copy:
Project URL
Publishable key
In Authentication → Providers → Email, keep email/password enabled.
Disable Confirm Email if you want signup to immediately land in the dashboard without email verification. Supabase’s current Next.js auth quickstart uses the App Router flow and email/password provider configuration for this setup. �
Supabase +1
How Free vs Pro works in this build
New users start on Free
Free users get:
tier = 'free'
monthly_generation_limit = 5
Pro users should have:
tier = 'pro'
monthly_generation_limit = null
billing_status = 'active'
Manual upgrade SQL for testing Pro
Run this in Supabase SQL Editor:
SQL
update public.profiles
set
  tier = 'pro',
  monthly_generation_limit = null,
  billing_status = 'active'
where email = 'user@example.com';
Gemini setup
Create the API key in Google AI Studio and place it in GEMINI_API_KEY. Google’s current Gemini docs say API keys are created and managed in AI Studio, and structured JSON outputs are supported through JSON Schema configuration. �
Google AI for Developers +1
Model recommendation
The default model in this codebase is gemini-2.5-flash, which is stable and has a current free-tier entry on Google’s pricing page. Google’s pricing docs also show other free-tier-capable Flash / Flash-Lite models if you want to swap later. �
Google AI for Developers
12. run instructions
exact npm install command
Bash
npm install
exact local env step
Create .env.local and paste:
Environment
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=https://your-project-ref.supabase.co
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=your-supabase-publishable-or-anon-key
GEMINI_API_KEY=your-google-ai-studio-api-key
GEMINI_MODEL=gemini-2.5-flash
NEXT_PUBLIC_PRO_UPGRADE_URL=https://your-checkout-or-billing-url.com
exact local run command
Bash
npm run dev
open locally
Plain text
http://localhost:3000
exact Vercel deploy steps
Push the project to GitHub
Import the repo into Vercel
Add the same environment variables in Vercel Project Settings
Deploy
Or deploy from CLI:
Bash
npm i -g vercel
vercel --prod
Vercel’s Hobby plan is currently the free plan for personal/small-scale apps, and Supabase’s pricing page still includes a free plan suitable for starter builds. �
Vercel +1
exact production note
This app is already wired for:
plan-aware UI locks
server-enforced monthly usage caps
DB tier tracking
pricing page
upgrade CTA routing